Data Interpretation

Y variable: CO2 emmission X variable: country, food_category, consumption Objective: Build regression model to predict carbon footprint of different type of food from various location

Exploratory Data Analysis

Firstly, we need to check the normality of y variable. I drew the density and qqplot graph help us seeing its distribution. The result is not ideal because the data is extremely right skewed. For further confirmation, I check its normality with shapiro test. it has a very small p value and it shows that the data is no ready for buidling linear regression model yet.

## 
##  Shapiro-Wilk normality test
## 
## data:  df$co2_emmission
## W = 0.51561, p-value < 2.2e-16

From Shapiro-Wilk normality test, we can see that original dataset is not normally distributed and not good for buidling linear regression model. Let’s check skewness of the the distribution of co2 emission. It shows strong positive skewness so I need to re-scale the dataset by transforming the data with log10. Here, I create a new column called “logco2” by transforming the co2emmision.

skewness(df$co2_emmission,na.rm=T)
## [1] 4.001336
df$logco2 <- log10(df$co2_emmission)

# Distribution of CO2 Emmission variable

g1 <- ggdensity(df, x = "co2_emmission", fill = "lightgray", title = "CONT") +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-3, 20)) +
  stat_overlay_normal_density(color = "red", linetype = "dashed")
g2 <- ggdensity(df, x = "logco2", fill = "lightgray", title = "CONT") +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-3, 5)) +
  stat_overlay_normal_density(color = "red", linetype = "dashed")
ggarrange(g1, g2, ncol = 2)
## Warning: Removed 653 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).
## Warning: Removed 653 rows containing non-finite values
## (stat_overlay_normal_density).
## Warning: Removed 254 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).
## Warning: Removed 44 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).
## Warning: Removed 44 rows containing non-finite values
## (stat_overlay_normal_density).

skewness(df$co2_emmission,na.rm=T)
## [1] 4.001336
skewness(df$logco2,na.rm=T)
## [1] NaN
skewness(df$consumption,na.rm = T)
## [1] 3.244597

As you can see from the graphs shown above, the skewness improved a lot by transforming with data with log 10. Reddashed line shows the distribution of the dataset is perfectly normalized. By transforming the datasets, the datset is almost normalized with some variance. Next, to make sure our datsets are valid to explore, I will clean the data by removing rows without CO2 emission record(because it is not possible for emission to be 0 if there is consumption).

For further exploration, I arbitrarily fit a linear model first and check the residuals and normality of the plot. Here, I split data into two train-test sets.

df <- df %>%  filter(co2_emmission >= 1)
ggplot(df,aes(food_category,logco2))+geom_boxplot()

ggplot(df,aes(food_category,consumption))+geom_boxplot()

# select outlier from the dataframe
mlconsump <- quantile(df[df[,"food_category"] == "Milk - inc. cheese","consumption"],probs = c(0.5,0.8,0.9,1))
df1<- df[!(df$food_category == "Milk - inc. cheese" & df$consumption>250),]

riceconsump <- quantile(df[df[,"food_category"] == "Rice","consumption"],probs = c(0.5,0.8,0.9,1))
df1 <- df[!(df[,"food_category"] == "Rice" & df$consumption>85.4),]

fishconsump <- quantile(df[df[,"food_category"] == "Fish","consumption"],probs = c(0.5,0.8,0.9,1))
df1 <- df[!(df[,"food_category"] == "Fish" & df$consumption>33.28),]
df1
# Split the data into training and test set
set.seed(123)
training.samples <- df1$logco2 %>%
  createDataPartition(p = 0.8, list = FALSE)
train.data  <- df1[training.samples, ]
test.data <- df1[-training.samples, ]
# Visualize plot of logco2 emmission vs consumption
g3 <- ggplot(train.data, aes( food_category,logco2) ) +
  geom_point() 
g4 <- ggplot(train.data, aes( consumption,logco2) ) +
  geom_point() +
  stat_smooth()

From this graph, we could see R^2 reach 0.77 but residuals are not normally distributed, From Normal Q-Q plot we can also discover there is heavy tail for this model. There is a curvature on the normality test, which may suggest that the relationship between dependent variable and independent variables may be polylinear rather than linear. I will discover the interaction effect between different variables in the datasets.

Interaction effect from country and consumption could also significantly affect total footprint of the model itself.Then, I want to check outliers from this model because normality plot show there is heavy tail, meaning there are some influential outliers in small co2 emission values.

Refit the dataset with fit2 and check if there is influential outliers in models
